of the Great War on the Western Front. Challenging long-standing myths about conscripts, Patrick Dennis examines whether these men arrived at the right moment, and in sufficient numbers, to make any significant difference to the success of the Canadian Corps. He examines the conscripts themselves, their journey to war, the battles in which they fought, and their largely undocumented sacrifice and heroism. Reluctant Warriors sheds new light on the success of the Military Service Act and provides fresh evidence that conscripts were good soldiers who fought valiantly and made a crucial contribution to the war effort.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDraftzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aDrafteeszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoldierszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xCasualtieszCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zCanada. 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh1 aGranatstein, J.L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311141793640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483599240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774835992423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774835992/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-141793-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles